`gameSound` becomes a *local* variable in both of your attempts. First it is local to `playTapSound()`, and thus not accessible from anywhere else, second it is local to `onCreate()`, and thus not even accessible from `playTapSound()` either.  
Create an object-level variable instead, outside of the methods (and thus available to all of them):

    private MediaPlayer gameSound;

    ... onCreate(){
      ...
      gameSound=MediaPlayer.create(this,R.raw.tapsound);
      ...
    }

    public void playTapSound(){
      gameSound.start();
    }

(However I do not know if it will run, this suggestion focuses on the compilation+visibility problem, I do not know if `start()` can be called multiple times - perhaps yes, perhaps you can simply put a stop immediately before the start, perhaps you have to track if it is still playing, and stop it only in that case).

(Side note: `final` makes a variable non-modifiable after initialization. It is not related to sharing variables between methods, and you do not need it here.)

